* ( ) Fix the chunk lifecycle
  Copying the entire `MeshJob` payload is not a good solution.
  An epoch/RCU style design can avoid most of that copying.
  "Job borrows mutable chunk storage" → "job reads an immutable published
  version whose reclamation is deferred"

  Updates publish a new version, while reclamation of the old version is 
  delayed until readers that could still hold pointers have exited.

** What an epoch scheme must protect
   ~ _Lifetime_: old voxel/bitfield storage must not be freed while a mesh
     job can still read it. This is the EBR/RCU part.
   ~ _Publication_: readers must see either the old fully initialized version
     or the new fully initialized version, never a half-written one.
   ~ _Stale result_: if meshing started from version `N`, but the chunk is
     now at version `N + 1`, the worker result should be dropped.

   @code zig
    ChunkSlot          // stable identity stored in the world map
    current: *ChunkVersion   // atomic pointer
    version: u64             // atomic generation for stale-result checks

    ChunkVersion       // immutable after publish
    voxels
    bitfields
    maybe mesh pointer, maybe not
   @end


